title: The Tennessean Midstate Top 10
text:
The Tennessean Midstate Top 10 The Tennessean Midstate Top 10 A look at the top high school football teams in Middle Tennessee, as ranked by The Tennessean, through Week 8 regular season: Sponsored by No. 10 FRA (8-0) Senior quarterback Spence Jones tallied 183 total yards and a pair of touchdowns Friday against Lipscomb as Panthers reeled off 24 unanswered second-half points to claim their eighth win of the season. Last week: No. 10 This week: Friday at Davidson Academy (6-1) No. 9 Hendersonville (7-1) The Commandos captured their third consecutive double-digit win Friday, blasting rival Gallatin 42-14 behind Jack Towe's three-touchdown effort, which included a 66-yard, first-quarter kickoff return for a score. Last week: No. 9 This week: Friday at Glencliff (2-5) No. 8 CPA (6-1) Lions quarterback Zack Weatherly accounted for 187 total yards, a four-yard rushing score and a 28-yard touchdown pass to Joseph Richard in Friday's 35-6 win over East Nashville. Last week: No. 8. This week: Friday at Greenbrier (4-4). No. 7 Ravenwood (6-1) The Raptors encountered little resistance from two-win Lebanon on Friday, rolling to a 45-point rout of the Blue Devils to claim their third consecutive Region 3-6A victory. Last week: No. 7 This week: Thursday vs. Overton (4-3) No. 6 Centennial (6-1) Junior Mondu Sawyers eclipsed the 100-yard mark for the fourth straight week, and the Cougars defense limited Brentwood to just 13 yards rushing in Friday's 24-10 triumph - the team's sixth in a row. Last week: No. 6 No. 5 Blackman (5-2) Senior running back Taeler Dowdy has rushed for 461 yards and six touchdowns in the last two games for the Blaze, who enjoyed a Week 8 bye. Last week: No. 5. This week: Friday at Siegel (0-7) No. 4 Independence (7-0) Andrew Bunch finally returned from his Week 2 elbow injury Friday, firing 21 completions for 252 yards and three touchdowns in a 46-15 win over Region 5-5A foe Shelbyville. Last week: No. 4 This week: Friday at Columbia (3-4) No. 3 MBA (7-1) Junior standout Ty Chandler got his yards - 189 to be exact - but the Big Red endured struggles on both sides of the ball in Friday's 48-14 defeat at Brentwood Academy. Last week: No. 1 This week: Friday at Baylor (6-1) No. 2 Oakland (6-1) The Patriots amassed five rushing touchdowns and nearly 300 yards on the ground Friday, and they surrendered a total of just 64 in their 49-6 thumping of Class 4A Brownsville. Last week: No. 3 This week: Friday vs. Riverdale (5-2) No. 1 Brentwood Academy (6-1) The Jeremiah Oatsvall-led Eagles delivered a big statement Friday at Carlton Flatt Field, piling up 48 points, 25 first downs and more than 550 yards in a decisive 34-point win over MBA. Last week: No. 2. This week: Friday at Father Ryan (4-3). Michael Murphy , mfmurphy@tennessean.com 12:47 p.m. CDT October 12, 2015 Buy Photo 131 CONNECT 21 TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE

10. Franklin Road Academy (8-0) — Senior quarterback Spence Jones tallied 183 total yards and a pair of touchdowns Friday against Lipscomb as Panthers reeled off 24 unanswered second-half points to claim their eighth win of the season. Last week: No. 10. This week: Friday at Davidson Academy (6-1). 
Hendersonville's Jack Towe. (Photo: Craig Harris / Gannett Tennessee) 
9. Hendersonville (7-1) — The Commandos captured their third consecutive double-digit win Friday, blasting rival Gallatin 42-14 behind Jack Towe’s three-touchdown effort, which included a 66-yard, first-quarter kickoff return for a score. Last week: No. 9. This week: Friday at Glencliff (2-5). Buy Photo 
CPA's Andrew Howard (10). (Photo: Larry McCormack / File / The Tennessean) 
8. CPA (6-1) — Lions quarterback Zack Weatherly accounted for 187 total yards, a four-yard rushing score and a 28-yard touchdown pass to Joseph Richard in Friday’s 35-6 win over East Nashville. Last week: No. 8. This week: Friday at Greenbrier (4-4). Buy Photo 
Ravenwood head coach Will Hester. (Photo: Jae S. Lee / File / The Tennessean) 
7. Ravenwood (6-1) — The Raptors encountered little resistance from two-win Lebanon on Friday, rolling to a 45-point rout of the Blue Devils to claim their third consecutive Region 3-6A victory. Last week: No. 7. This week: Thursday vs. Overton (4-3). Buy Photo 
Centennial running back Mondu Sawyers (8). (Photo: Shelley Mays / The Tennessean) 
6. Centennial (7-1) — Junior Mondu Sawyers eclipsed the 100-yard mark for the fourth straight week, and the Cougars defense limited Brentwood to just 13 yards rushing in Friday’s 24-10 triumph — the team’s sixth in a row. Last week: No. 6. This week: Bye. 
Blackman head coach David Watson. (Photo: Helen Comer / File / Gannett Tennessee) 
5. Blackman (5-2) — Senior running back Taeler Dowdy has rushed for 461 yards and six touchdowns in the last two games for the Blaze, who enjoyed a Week 8 bye. Last week : No. 5. This week: Friday at Siegel (0-7). Buy Photo 
Independence quarterback Andrew Bunch (10). (Photo: George Walker IV / File / The Tennessean) 
4. Independence (7-0) — Andrew Bunch finally returned from his Week 2 elbow injury Friday, firing 21 completions for 252 yards and three touchdowns in a 46-15 win over Region 5-5A foe Shelbyville. Last week: No. 4. This week: Friday at Columbia (3-4). 
MBA running back Ty Chandler fights for extra yardage Friday against Brentwood Academy. (Photo: Michael Murphy / The Tennssean.) 
3. MBA (7-1) — Junior standout Ty Chandler got his yards — 189 to be exact — but the Big Red endured struggles on both sides of the ball in Friday’s 48-14 defeat at Brentwood Academy. Last week: No. 1. This week: Bye. 
Lazarius Patterson and the Patriots piled up close to 300 yards rushing in Friday's win. (Photo: Tom Beckwith / Gannett Tennessee) 
2. Oakland (6-1) — The Patriots amassed five rushing touchdowns and nearly 300 yards on the ground Friday, and they surrendered a total of just 64 in their 49-6 thumping of Class 4A Brownsville. Last week: No. 3. This week: Friday vs. Riverdale (5-2). Buy Photo 
Brentwood Academy quarterback Jeremiah Oatsvall. (Photo: Michael Murphy / The Tennessean) 
1. Brentwood Academy (6-1) — The Jeremiah Oatsvall-led Eagles delivered a big statement Friday at Carlton Flatt Field, piling up 48 points, 25 first downs and more than 550 yards in a decisive 34-point win over MBA.
